title: For Sale:  Weatherby Mark V Accumark Ultra Lightweight with Leupold Vari X 2 3X9X40 in 270 Winchester
postcontent: Weatherby Mark 5 Accumark Ultra Lightweight with Leupold 3X9X40mm Vari X 2 scope. Fluted barrel and bolt with all the weight saving features you will ever find on a gun. Of course it is a tack driver because Weatherby guarantees that with every Mark 5 they sell. Maybe I got lucky but this one shoots Winchester Supreme 130 Grain ballistic tips into tiny little clover leaf groups at 100 yards. Probably shoots other ammo just as well but never saw the reason to buy anything else. Fired maybe 20 times since I have owned it (2005). First 10 shots I shot and cleaned after each round letting the barrel cool completely while adjusting the scope. Fired 3 and cleaned with all 3 inside the little red square on the target. SHot 3 more to fine tune the scope for 2 inches high at 100 and you could cover the group with a quarter. Probably hunted less than 10 times with it over the years which means it sat beside me and a round bale of hay in the pasture waiting for last light. By far the lightest gun I have ever owned and in all honesty it kicks harder than any 270 Winchester I have ever owned too. That's not saying much because the 270 win is pretty mild anyway and the nice recoil pad does the rest. Besides, I have carried a gun many more hours than I have ever fired one and I'll take a little kick at the bench sighting in to save me that much weight. Of course the scope has the lifetime warranty, click adjustments and is the brightest around. My Blue book shows the gun MSRP at 1919$ and 1550$ used but this is a 2011 version and thats without the scope, bases, rings, etc. Weatherby guns don't lose value so hunt with a great gun and make a little profit when your done or leave a gun to the grandchild they will be proud to own. You can get one on Gunbroker.com for 1600-1700$ and put the scope, bases, and rings on for another 350$ or you can buy this one for 1500$ cash. Price is firm for obvious reasons and I can't hold it. First 1500$ gets you the gun of a lifetime with the best scope money can buy and it is all made here in America. Yes! This is a California gun and says so right on the receiver. Best of all, it shoots 270 Winchester that you can buy from anywhere including the local marts, sport shops and anywhere online and you can hunt any animal in North America with this caliber, except those big Brown Grizzlies. Probably could kill one with a 270 but if you need something bigger for bear country I have a NIB Kimber in 300 WSM Classic Select with AA Fancy French Claro Presentation wood for 1200$. Don't regret letting this one get away. I would keep it myself but it is just setting in the safe and hasn't seen the field in a few years. I plan to keep a couple of family heirlooms and the rest will go. Let it breathe and hunt with a Weatherby! Or bow up and be the Main Damn Rod and have the Weatherby and the Kimber. One for the good weather and pretty days and the Weatherby for any weather you want.

postcontent: Like new Browning Gold Stalker in 12 gauge that will shoot ay 12 gauge shell made today. Lead, STeel, Bismuth, Tungsten, whatever. Bought it as my all around shotgun for Waterfowl, Turkey, Dove, etc. Duck hunted twice and gave that up. You couldn't pay me to go Turkey hunting again and I have an old A5 that I can't help but use if and when I ever get to dove hunt again. Cleaning out the safes and I'll keep a couple favorites but this one has to go. Has all the choke tubes for either barrel. Full, Mod, IC, and of course an XF Extended Turkey Choke. Kicks more like a 20 gauge than a 12 and it handles very well. title: For Sale:  Winchester Super X-2 NWTF 12 gauge 3.5 inch Camo shotgun with Fiber Optic Sights and all the choke tubes. Fired 3 times to pattern gun and hunted 1 time.
postcontent: Gun is in flawless condition with perfect camo pattern. Shoots 3.5 inch, 3 inch, and 2 3/4 shells with no adjustments and has the recoil of a 20 gauge shooting light loads. Truth is, I got all fired up about turkey hunting because my brother talked me into it. Got this gun, and a turkey barrel for another shotgun. Mastered the calls for a year, watched all the video, had the perfect camo, great places to hunt back home in Oklahoma. Put the birds to bed that night, woke up and went to get 'em. Owl swooped in and stole by foam decoy and trashed it(should have stopped then). No birds to be found so we made a little move near the water. Found a nice tree and set up again. Apparently the tree belonged to a family of rattlesnakes and in the process of high tailing it out managed to pick up about 20 or so ticks. Most of which found the inside of my naval and gave me these beautiful red rings all across my stomach. Managed to get bit by a spider while I changed at the truck and tried to pick all the ticks off. So the gun has no use to me. You couldn't pay me to turkey hunt again. I'll just buy one in November and let the wife cook it up and not worry about what is going to bite me next. I paid way too much for the gun and I'm embarrassed enough that there's no way I'll tell you. It does pattern very well and you can even have the 7 or 8 shells I have left from the 10 round box I bought for the "great turkey hunt". There are a couple on Gunbroker.com between 950$ and 1100$ but you can just take this one away for 800$ cash. You get the tubes, the gun, the manual, the leftover shells and you can have all of the turkey hunting to yourself as well. It really is a great gun and when I bought it Outdoor Life had named it the best Turkey gun ever built. Anyway, the price is firm for obvious reasons and I expect it to go soon so I can't hold it. It obviously doubles as a great waterfowl/goose gun but you can shoot dove all day long with 1 ounce loads and then rabbit/squirrel/quail hunt in the afternoon with whatever your game load and then load up some 3 inch OO buck for self defense. I was amazed at the light recoil even with the heavy Turkey load. This is really one gun that can do it all from January through December, and yes, they even make a rifled barrel for the gun as well. This is actually the same gun as a Browning Gold Stalker 3.5 inch. I have one of each and yes, the parts are identical. In fact, the barrel has the exact same imprint that it is made in Belgium as the Browning Autoloader I have. Come get your gun and you can have the woods all to yourself this spring. I'm through getting up at 0400 to hunt ducks and geese as well so even more room for you to enjoy the great outdoors this fall. I'll stick to things with horns that I can shoot from my pop up blind in my old age and let you young bucks fight the snakes, ticks and spiders. My 2011 Blue Book of Gun Values has it listed at 1236$ it will go to the first 800$ cash and I guarantee you that this gun will serve you well.

title: For Sale:  Blast from the Past - Beretta Mod. 950BS Jetfire in .25 ACP. **FINAL REDUCTION**
postcontent: Beretta Mod. 950BS in .25 ACP. - Private sale of an older classic Beretta in good condition. Made in Italy. When I called Beretta, they advised the gun's serial number predates their record keeping, and that based upon its features it had to have been manufactured sometime between 1950 and 1959. Bore is in excellent shape. I don't think it was shot much. Has a tip up barrel. Perfect gun for someone that is disabled, or has difficulty racking a slide (elderly, those with arthritis, small women etc...). You never rack the slide to shot this gun. You just drop a round in the tip up barrel, and once fired, it automatically cycles the next round. For a “mouse” gun, it has a large 8+1 capacity.  The Beretta is only single action, (where the hammer resets due to the blowback from the fired cartridge, and not from pulling the trigger – The trigger only releases the hammer, which equals a light and smooth trigger). Very nice aged look. Nice, and small for concealed carry. Carry it with Hornady “magic” bullets, and it will be just as effective as a 40 caliber. I already have two (2) good shooting .25 acp caliber guns, and can't really justify keeping this one. Own a classic Beretta for only $155 (reduced). Private sale. Must be over 21, have a Florida D/L and be legally able to own a firearm. Sale will must take place at my office in Palm Harbor. Don't waste my time if you are not willing to sign a bill of sale, or won't allow me to make a copy of your Florida d/license. If you want to spend a little less, I am willing to keep the Beretta, and would sell one of my Ravens that is in like new condition (with box), with only about 150 rds through it for $130.00.
